Decision Trees Classification using Text Data¶

Introduction¶

In this section, I will introduce the process of applying the Decision Trees (DT) to text data classification, the dataset I use for DT classfication, as well as the the classfication results.

The text data I will be using for DT classification is the Twitter reponse dataset (tweetEN_clean.csv) and its count vectorizer dataset (tweetEN_CountVectorizer.csv) that was cleaned and used in the previous sections, which can be found here. The Twitter reponse dataset contains 11 attributes. The labels of this dataset are multiclasses that contain three classes: "negative", "positive" and "neutral".

A snapshot of the dataset will be shown in the class distribution section below.

What is Decision Tree?¶

A Decision Tree is a descision support tool that uses a tree-like model of decision and their possible possible consequences, including chance event outcomes, resource costs, and utility. Source: Wikipedia

Decision Trees (DTs) are non-parametric supervised learning method used for classification and regression. The deeper the tree, the more complex the decision rules and the fitter the model.

Advantages of Decision Trees (DT):

  • Simple to interpret and implement
  • Trees can be visualized easily
  • Requires little data preparation (data normalization not required)
  • Able to handle multi-output problems
  • Able to handle both numerical and categorical data
  • Possible to validate a model using statistical tests

Disadvantages of Decision Trees (DT):

  • Tend to overfit
  • Can be unstable since small variations in the data might result in completely different results
  • Not very good at extrapolation
  • Might create biased trees if some classes dominate

Source: scikit-learn.org

Baseline Model for Comparison¶

In this part, I will run a random classifier on your data and output accuracy, precision, and recall values in order to have a better preview of the possible classfication results using this dataset. The code of the random classifier is provided by Professor James Hickman.

In [ ]:
def generate_label_data(class_labels, weights, N=10000):
    # e.g. class_labels=[0,1] weights=[0.2, 0.8] (should sum to one)
    
    y = random.choices(class_labels, weights = weights, k = N)
    print("-----GENERATING DATA-----")
    print("unique entries:",Counter(y).keys())
    print("count of labels:",Counter(y).values()) # counts the elements' frequency
    print("probability of labels:",np.fromiter(Counter(y).values(), dtype=float)/len(y)) # counts the elements' frequency 
    return y
    
    
 ## RANDOM CLASSIFIER
def random_classifier(y_data): 
    ypred=[]
    max_label=np.max(y_data); #print(max_label) 
    for i in range(0,len(y_data)):
        ypred.append(int(np.floor((max_label+1)*np.random.uniform(0,1))))
    print("-----RANDOM CLASSIFIER-----")
    print("count of prediction:",Counter(ypred).values()) # counts the elements' frequency
    print("probability of prediction:",np.fromiter(Counter(ypred).values(), dtype=float)/len(y_data)) # counts the elements' frequency
    print("accuracy",accuracy_score(y_data, ypred))
    print("percision, recall, fscore,",precision_recall_fscore_support(y_data, ypred))

Using random classifier on the Tweet text data based on the weights calculated above to get accuracy, precision, and recall values. In this part, I used 0 to represent the label "positive", 1 as "negative", and 2 as "neutral".

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay

def confusion_plot(y_data, y_pred):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_data, y_pred)
    print('ACCURACY:', accuracy_score(y_data, y_pred))
    print('RECALL SCORE:', recall_score(y_data, y_pred, average=None))
    print('PRECISION SCORE:', precision_score(y_data, y_pred, average=None))  
    print(cm)
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm)
    disp.plot()

Hyper-Parameter Adjustment¶

The "max_depth" hyper-parameter controls the number of layers in the tree. In this part, I will try to find the set of hyper-parameters with the lowest training AND test error by iterating over "max_depth".

In [ ]:
test_results=[]
train_results=[]

for num_layer in range(1,30):
    model = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=num_layer)
    model = model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    yp_train=model.predict(x_train)
    yp_test=model.predict(x_test)

    # print(y_pred.shape)
    test_results.append([num_layer,accuracy_score(y_test, yp_test),recall_score(y_test, yp_test, average = None)])
    train_results.append([num_layer,accuracy_score(y_train, yp_train),recall_score(y_train, yp_train, average = None)])

Plotting accuracy scores and recall scores based on different max_dephts (from 1 to 30 )of the tree to find out the most optimal max_depth for the tree.

Train Optimal Model & Visualize the Tree¶

Re-train the decision tree using the optimal hyper-parameter obtained from the plot above, which is the max_depth of 5.

def plot_tree(model,X,Y):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(25,20))
    _ = tree.plot_tree(model, 
                    filled=True)
    plt.show()

Conclusion¶

Based on the classification reports above, we can see that the predictive performance of the Decision Trees (DT) classifier on the testing data is not ideal and even a bit poor with a 40% accuracy. The possible reasons that caused this poor prediction are:

  • the very limited data size
  • the heavily imbalanced classes
  • the feasibility of the model for the text data
